"""
MKT Ezekiel chapters 37–39 — three-tier translation written directly to draft JSON files.
Run: python3 scripts/mkt-ezekiel-37-39.py

=== CHAPTER OVERVIEW ===
Ch 37: Two visions/oracles.
  vv. 1–14: Valley of Dry Bones — the Spirit of Yahweh carries Ezekiel to a valley of desiccated
    human bones. Commanded to prophesy, Ezekiel speaks the word; the bones reassemble, flesh
    returns, but there is no breath. A second prophetic command calls the four winds/breath (רוּחַ),
    and the vast army comes to life. Interpretation: the whole house of Israel in exile, whose hope
    is lost, will be raised from the grave of exile and returned to the land with Yahweh's Spirit
    placed in them (v.14).
  vv. 15–28: Two Sticks — a symbolic act: one stick labeled Judah, one labeled Joseph (Ephraim).
    Joined in the prophet's hand, they become one. Meaning: the divided kingdom (split since
    Jeroboam, 930 BCE) will be reunited under one king — the Davidic servant. The section ends
    with the covenant-of-peace formula, the divine dwelling, and the covenant formula
    ("I will be their God, they will be my people").
Ch 38: Oracle against Gog of Magog — eschatological invasion.
  vv. 1–9: Yahweh summons Gog from the north with his vast coalition; Yahweh himself puts hooks
    in Gog's jaws and draws him forward against the restored, peacefully dwelling Israel.
  vv. 10–23: Gog's evil plan; the trading nations watch; Yahweh's fury; cosmic earthquake;
    self-defeating panic among Gog's forces; plague, blood, hail, fire, and sulfur. Purpose:
    Yahweh magnifies and sanctifies himself before all nations.
Ch 39: Gog's defeat, burial, and aftermath.
  vv. 1–16: Gog disarmed and slaughtered on Israel's mountains; seven years burning weapons;
    seven months burying corpses in the Valley of Hamon-gog; dedicated burial teams; a city
    named Hamonah.
  vv. 17–20: Yahweh's eschatological sacrifice feast — birds and beasts summoned to eat the
    mighty of the earth.
  vv. 21–29: Theological retrospect and promise — the nations understand the exile was divine
    judgment, not defeat. Yahweh restores Jacob's fortunes, pours out his Spirit, and will never
    again hide his face.

=== CONTESTED-TERM DECISIONS ===

- H3068 (יהוה): "LORD" in L/M throughout. "Yahweh" in T — especially in the recognition
  formula, oracle-opening formulas, and direct speech. Consistent with all prior Ezekiel scripts.

- H136 + H3069 (אֲדֹנָי יְהוִה / Lord GOD): "Lord GOD" in L/M. "Lord Yahweh" in T. Consistent
  with all prior Ezekiel scripts.

- H7307 (רוּחַ) — THE central contested term of ch. 37. Hebrew uses one word for Spirit, wind,
  and breath. The Valley of Dry Bones exploits all three meanings simultaneously and deliberately:
  * 37:1 — "the Spirit of the LORD" (transport-vision; divine Spirit carries the prophet)
  * 37:5,6,8,10,14 — "breath" (the breath of life returning to dead bodies)
  * 37:9 (four uses) — the great triple-entendre: addressed as "O breath/wind/Spirit," called
    from the "four winds," commanded to "breathe." L uses "wind" for the address/directions and
    "breath" for what enters. M resolves toward "breath" as the life-giving agent. T explicitly
    names all three registers.
  * 37:14 — "my Spirit" (divine Spirit placed in the people — transition from physical breath to
    the gift of the divine Spirit)
  * 38:9 — uses H7722 (שׁוֹאָה = storm), not רוּחַ; no decision needed there.
  * 39:29 — "my Spirit" poured out — the eschatological Spirit-gift closing the Gog oracle.

- H5387 (נָשִׂיא) in 37:25: "prince" in L/M/T. Ezekiel consistently uses נָשִׂיא (prince) for the
  coming Davidic ruler throughout the book, never מֶלֶךְ (king), reserving full kingship for
  Yahweh alone. T notes this explicitly in v.25.

- H7494 (רַעַשׁ) in 37:7 and 38:19: "shaking" / "earthquake" — the physical shaking that
  accompanies the divine word and divine presence.

- H1285 (בְּרִית) in 37:26: "covenant of peace" — בְּרִית שָׁלוֹם, the covenantal formula. "Covenant"
  in all three tiers. T expands the שָׁלוֹם to include wholeness/completeness.

- H4908 (מִשְׁכָּן) in 37:27: "tabernacle" (L), "dwelling" (M), "dwelling / tabernacle" (T).
  The divine dwelling among the people is the Sinai typology fulfilled. John 1:14 (ἐσκήνωσεν)
  echoes this passage.

- H4720 (מִקְדָּשׁ) in 37:26,28: "sanctuary" in all three tiers.

- Recognition formula (וְיָדְעוּ כִּי-אֲנִי יְהוָה): L: "they shall know that I am the LORD";
  M: "they will know that I am the LORD"; T: "they will know that I am Yahweh."
  Consistent with all prior Ezekiel scripts.

- H39:2 (וְשִׁשֵּׁאתִיךָ): The traditional KJV "leave but the sixth part of thee" is text-critically
  doubtful. The root is uncertain; many scholars read it as "drive you on / lead you forward."
  LXX supports a leading/driving sense. Rendered "drive you on" in L/M; T notes the variant.

- H1463 (גּוֹג) / H4031 (מָגוֹג): "Gog" / "Magog" in all three tiers. T notes the theological
  role without speculative historical identification.

- H6918 (קָדוֹשׁ) in 39:7: "the Holy One in Israel" — not "of Israel." Yahweh's holiness is
  located and present, not merely attributed. This distinction matters and is preserved in T.

- H2077 (זֶבַח) in 39:17-19: "sacrifice" in all three tiers — Yahweh summons birds and beasts
  to his "sacrificial feast" (the bodies of Gog's slain army). The ironic feast imagery: the
  mighty become the sacrificial animals.

=== ASPECT / TENSE NOTES ===

- Valley of Dry Bones (37:1-14): Prophetic perfect for completed vision-action ("I prophesied,"
  "the bones came together"); divine speech in imperfect = future promise.
- Two Sticks (37:15-28): Present-tense commands (symbolic act) + future divine promises.
- Gog oracle (38-39): Predominantly future — Yahweh announces what he will do. Hebrew imperfect
  rendered as future certainty throughout.
- 39:8 "it is come and it is done" — prophetic perfect: the future event spoken of as already
  accomplished, expressing absolute certainty.

=== OT INTERTEXTUALITY ===

- 37:1-14 — Gen 2:7 echo: Yahweh breathing life into formed dust. The valley reverses Genesis'
  creation-death cycle. T surfaces this.
- 37:14 — Joel 2:28-29 (Spirit poured out on all flesh). T notes the forward trajectory.
  Acts 2 (Pentecost) reads Joel reading Ezekiel.
- 37:27 — John 1:14 (ἐσκήνωσεν ἐν ἡμῖν) echoes מִשְׁכָּנִי עֲלֵיהֶם. The tabernacle theme
  connects Exodus → Ezekiel 37 → John.
- 38:22 — Sodom judgment imagery (Gen 19:24): fire, sulfur, overwhelmingly rain. T notes.
- 39:17-20 — Rev 19:17-18 echoes this passage directly: the "great supper of God" for birds.
  T notes the apocalyptic trajectory.
- 39:29 — Joel 2:28-29 again; 39:29 is the direct OT anchor for the Pentecost sermon (Acts 2).
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT  = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent
DRAFT = ROOT / 'data' / 'translation' / 'draft'

def load(tier, book):
    p = DRAFT / tier / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save(tier, book, data):
    p = DRAFT / tier / f'{book}.json'
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_tier(existing, new_data, tier_key):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, tiers in verses.items():
            existing[ch][v] = tiers[tier_key]

